   "regular-body" : "<p><a href=\"http://what-hath-science-wrought.tumblr.com/post/184099333449/wondersseen-you-know-the-main-problem-with\" class=\"tumblr_blog\">what-hath-science-wrought</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://wondersseen.tumblr.com/post/184087816712/you-know-the-main-problem-with-the-live-action\" class=\"tumblr_blog\">wondersseen</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You know the main problem with theÂ âlive actionâ Lion King? Why it looks so lifeless?</p>\n<p>The hyper realistic style is actually limiting the animators, rather than freeing them. The style makes it much harder to have memorable character designs and good expressions. Real lions donât need to do things like emote in a way that humans can understand â but characters in a film do.Â The original movie was more cartoony not due to animation limitations of the time, but because that style <i>genuinely serves the story better.</i></p>\n<p>To show you what I mean, compare these two shots of Simba, from right after Scar saysÂ ârun away and never return.â</p>\n<figure class=\"tmblr-full\" data-orig-height=\"276\" data-orig-width=\"480\"><img src=\"https://66.media.tumblr.com/e476c8bb1ec3eff37e17916dfe24fbb6/tumblr_inline_ppr7k1uccV1vhkpq2_1280.gif\" data-orig-height=\"276\" data-orig-width=\"480\"/></figure><p>Here is a clear reaction, with a strong beat for us to connect with before the character makes a decision. Even without any dialogue, even without any context, you can understand the emotion there just by the expression and the mannerisms. Is it realistic? No! Heâs bright yellow and has eyebrows. But do we empathize with him? Yes!</p>\n<figure class=\"tmblr-full\" data-orig-height=\"259\" data-orig-width=\"480\"><img src=\"https://66.media.tumblr.com/e8c12251bdd26823f3fd40b9299d5dbd/tumblr_inline_ppr7ieMsUP1vhkpq2_1280.gif\" data-orig-height=\"259\" data-orig-width=\"480\"/></figure><p>Meanwhile, here isâ¦ a lion. Turning and running. No expression, no beats, no character moments, <i>nothing</i>. He actually <i>canât </i>express himself because the animators are locked into the realistic style. If they tried to animate a strong expression as warranted for the scene, it would look terrible. Is it realistic? Hell yeah! Look at those textures! Look at that fur! But do we empathize with him? â¦nah. Not really.</p>\n<p>To conclude: when youâre retelling Hamlet with a bunch of animated lions, cartoonish-ness is your friend, not your enemy.</p>\n<figure class=\"tmblr-full\" data-orig-height=\"450\" data-orig-width=\"800\"><img src=\"https://66.media.tumblr.com/c9cefd0ef084231a948d72d88d5c0058/tumblr_inline_ppr8kvA4dY1vhkpq2_1280.png\" data-orig-height=\"450\" data-orig-width=\"800\"/></figure></blockquote>\n<p>and this on the heels of spider-verse showing us exactly what cg animation is capable of. If youâre chasing realism for realismâs sake, just make like a normal movie.  </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Excellently said. Also, isnât âhere is a lionâ the translation of the opening of âCircle of Lifeâ?</p>",
